== Mythological Account == Nagasunehiko's sister, {{ill|Mikashikiyahime|ja|三炊屋媛|12=draft|12=draft}}, became the wife of Nigihayahi no Mikoto, who had descended from the heavens at Mount Takeru in [[Kawachi Province]] aboard the [[Ame-no-Iwafune|Heavenly Rock Ship]]. She later bore him {{ill|Umashimaji no Mikoto|ja|宇摩志麻遅命|12=draft|12=draft}}.
When Emperor Jimmu reached the [[Hirakata|White Shoulder Port]] of [[Naniwa Province]], he was confronted by Nagasunehiko at Kusakae Hill. During this battle, Jimmu's brother, {{ill|Hikoiwase|ja|彦五瀬命|12=draft|12=draft}}, was wounded by an arrow and later died.
Subsequently, Jimmu's forces defeated other local leaders, including the {{ill|Eighty Bandit Chiefs|ja|八十梟帥|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Aniiso|ja|兄磯城|12=draft|12=draft}}. Nagasunehiko's forces were finally defeated when a divine golden kite perched on Jimmu's bowstring, dazzling and disorienting the enemy.
In the Nihon Shoki, Nagasunehiko questioned Jimmu's claim to divine descent, citing his allegiance to Nigihayahi no Mikoto, who had married his sister and borne a son. After comparing divine tokens such as the {{ill|Heavenly Feathered Arrow|ja|天羽々矢|12=draft|12=draft}} and confirming Jimmu's legitimacy, Nagasunehiko refused to submit and was slain by Nigihayahi.
