{{Unreferenced|date=December 2024}} {{Infobox noble | name = Nagasunehiko | image = | image_size = | caption = | era = Ancient | birth_date = Unknown | death_date = Before the enthronement of [[Emperor Jimmu]] | alias = Tomino Nagasunehiko, Tomibiko, Nagasunehiko, Torimihiko | titles = | deification = | burial_place = | Rank = | lord = [[Nigihayahi no Mikoto]] | clan = | parents = | siblings = Sister: {{ill|Mikashikiyahime|ja|三炊屋媛|12=draft}} | spouse = | children = | notable_facts = Resisted Emperor Jimmu during the [[Eastern Expedition of Emperor Jimmu]] }}
'''Nagasunehiko''' (長髄彦) is a legendary figure from [[Japanese mythology]]. He is known as one of the leaders of [[Yamato Province]] who opposed [[Emperor Jimmu]] during the [[Jimmu's Eastern Expedition|Eastern Expedition of Emperor Jimmu]] but was ultimately defeated.
== Overview == The name '''Nagasunehiko''' appears in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}}, while the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft}} refers to him as '''Tomino Nagasunehiko''' (登美能那賀須泥毘古) or '''Tomibiko''' (登美毘古). He is described as a leader of the [[gōzoku]] (regional clans) in the Yamato region who resisted Emperor Jimmu's forces.
According to the Kojiki, Nagasunehiko did not resist Emperor Jimmu and instead pledged allegiance when his lord, {{ill|Nigihayahi no Mikoto|ja|饒速日命|12=draft}}, submitted to Jimmu. In contrast, the Nihon Shoki depicts him continuing to fight even after verifying his lord's divine authority, ultimately leading to his death at Nigihayahi's hands.
In the {{ill|Sendai Kujihongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|12=draft}}, Emperor Jimmu confronts Nagasunehiko after detouring around the [[Kii Peninsula]], at which point Nigihayahi is already deceased. Nagasunehiko refuses to submit despite admonishment by {{ill|Umashimaji no Mikoto|ja|宇摩志麻遅命|12=draft}} and is killed.
The Nihon Shoki mentions that "Nagasune" was originally a place name.
== Mythological Account == Nagasunehiko's sister, {{ill|Mikashikiyahime|ja|三炊屋媛|12=draft}}, became the wife of Nigihayahi no Mikoto, who had descended from the heavens at Mount Takeru in [[Kawachi Province]] aboard the [[Ame-no-Iwafune|Heavenly Rock Ship]]. She later bore him {{ill|Umashimaji no Mikoto|ja|宇摩志麻遅命|12=draft}}.
When Emperor Jimmu reached the [[Hirakata|White Shoulder Port]] of [[Naniwa Province]], he was confronted by Nagasunehiko at Kusakae Hill. During this battle, Jimmu's brother, {{ill|Hikoiwase|ja|彦五瀬命|12=draft}}, was wounded by an arrow and later died.
Subsequently, Jimmu's forces defeated other local leaders, including the {{ill|Eighty Bandit Chiefs|ja|八十梟帥|12=draft}} and {{ill|Aniiso|ja|兄磯城|12=draft}}. Nagasunehiko's forces were finally defeated when a divine golden kite perched on Jimmu's bowstring, dazzling and disorienting the enemy.
In the Nihon Shoki, Nagasunehiko questioned Jimmu's claim to divine descent, citing his allegiance to Nigihayahi no Mikoto, who had married his sister and borne a son. After comparing divine tokens such as the {{ill|Heavenly Feathered Arrow|ja|天羽々矢|12=draft}} and confirming Jimmu's legitimacy, Nagasunehiko refused to submit and was slain by Nigihayahi.
== Medieval Legends == Medieval texts like the {{ill|Soga Monogatari|ja|曽我物語|12=draft}} mention Nagasunehiko's brother, {{ill|Abihiko|ja|安日彦|12=draft}}. The [[Andō clan]], later the {{ill|Akita family|ja|秋田家|12=draft}}, claimed descent from Nagasunehiko.
== Modern Interpretations == Some theories suggest Nagasunehiko was a local leader in the {{ill|Tomi region|ja|鳥見郷|12=draft}} (modern {{ill|Ikoma|ja|生駒市|12=draft}} and {{ill|Nara|ja|奈良市|12=draft}}). A monument in {{ill|Shiraniwadai|ja|白庭台|12=draft}}, Ikoma, marks the site traditionally associated with his stronghold.
Other interpretations propose that Nagasunehiko's resistance represents a symbolic struggle between indigenous and imperial forces during the Yamato state's consolidation.
== Shrines and Legacy == Local legends and shrines such as the {{ill|Soe Mie Kenza Shrine|ja|添御縣坐神社|12=draft}} are believed to honor Nagasunehiko. These sites commemorate his role in local history and mythology.
